This incorporates some of the post-merge feedback for PR #3691, namely, it adds an `InputStream` and `OutputStream` protocol which are used as the return types for `InputFile.open()` and `OutputFile.create()`.

Using a `typing.Protocol` (thanks for the suggestion @emkornfield) allows for flexibility of these implementations. Validation is essentially structural subtyping (aka "static duck typing"). This will be very handy when developing FileIO implementations that heavily rely on third party libraries. It should allow us to inform the implementer of the interface without requiring them to generate a wrapper class that inherits from an ABC and wraps the file-like objects provided by the third party library.

To demonstrate, an object that matches the protocol will return `True` for an isinstance check, even if the type of the object does not directly inherit from that class:
```py
from typing import Protocol, runtime_checkable


@runtime_checkable
class Speaker(Protocol):
    def speak(self) -> str:
        ...

class Greeter:
    def speak(self):
        return "Hello!"
        
greeter = Greeter()
isinstance(greeter, Speaker)  # True
```

The purpose of the `runtime_checkable` decorator is to allow for the runtime `isinstance` check. This gives an implementer the option to validate that `InputStream` or `OutputStream` is fully implemented (see an example of how I added this to the `LocalFileIO` implementation in commit [2003f73](https://github.com/apache/iceberg/pull/4021/commits/2003f73c125cc33d72b1d0af967f092d89daae4c#diff-3ced008699fedda78712dccd78a398136c8a279342fde9ac9c1713ddfd891339R58)).

This would be a replacement for having to do something like...
```py
class SmartOpenInputFileStream(InputFileStream):

    def __init__(self, smart_open_file_stream):
        self._file_stream = smart_open_file_stream

    @property
    def file_stream(self):
        return self._file_stream

    def readable(self) -> bool:
        return self.file_stream.readable()
```
...which wraps the file-like object returned by smartopen's [open](https://github.com/RaRe-Technologies/smart_open/blob/59d3a6079b523c030c78a3935622cf94405ce052/smart_open/smart_open_lib.py#L100) function.

### Python 3.7 support

It's important to note that `typing.Protocol` was introduced in Python 3.8 ([PEP 544](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0544/)) but we're currently supporting Python 3.7+. Python 3.7's [end of life](https://endoflife.date/python) is scheduled for about a year and half from now. Btw, this is the explanation for the tests failing for this PR. :)

Curious to get everyone's thoughts!
